{% set effectCode %}<p>This text has an
  <span data-effect="highlight" data-trigger="scroll">animated highlight</span>
  effect applied.
</p>{% endset %}

{% set statusCode %}<span class="status" data-status="success">Deployed</span>
<span class="status" data-status="warning">Pending review</span>
<span class="status" data-status="error">Build failed</span>
<span class="status" data-status="inactive">Offline</span>{% endset %}

{% set translateCode %}<p>Install <span translate="no">Vanilla Breeze</span> via npm.</p>
<p>Your username is <span translate="no">tpowell42</span>.</p>{% endset %}

{% set visuallyHiddenCode %}<p>Price:
  <span class="visually-hidden">Was </span>
  <s>$99.99</s>
  <span class="visually-hidden">Now </span>
  $79.99
</p>{% endset %}

{% set blockProgressCode %}<span class="block-progress" role="meter"
      aria-valuenow="70" aria-valuemin="0" aria-valuemax="100"
      aria-label="Progress">
  <span aria-hidden="true" data-filled>███████</span>
  <span aria-hidden="true" data-empty>░░░</span>
  <small>70%</small>
</span>{% endset %}

{% set statusCssCode %}.status {
  display: inline-flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 0.4em;
  font-size: var(--font-size-sm);

  &::before {
    content: "\25CF"; /* filled circle */
    font-size: 0.7em;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  &[data-status="success"]::before { color: var(--color-success); }
  &[data-status="warning"]::before { color: var(--color-warning); }
  &[data-status="error"]::before   { color: var(--color-error); }

  &[data-status="inactive"]::before {
    content: "\25CB"; /* empty circle */
  }
  &[data-status="check"]::before {
    content: "\2714"; /* check mark */
    color: var(--color-success);
  }
  &[data-status="fail"]::before {
    content: "\2718"; /* cross mark */
    color: var(--color-error);
  }
}{% endset %}

{% set antiPatternCode %}<!-- Wrong: span for layout -->
<span class="header">Site Title</span>

<!-- Right: use semantic element -->
<h1>Site Title</h1>

<!-- Wrong: span for emphasis -->
<span style="font-weight: bold">Important</span>

<!-- Right: use semantic element -->
<strong>Important</strong>{% endset %}

<section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;span&gt;</code> element is a generic inline container with no inherent semantics. Like <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> for block content, <code>&lt;span&gt;</code> should be used only when no semantic element fits the need.</p>
    <p><strong>Prefer semantic elements first:</strong> <a href="/docs/elements/native/em/"><code>&lt;em&gt;</code></a>, <a href="/docs/elements/native/strong/"><code>&lt;strong&gt;</code></a>, <a href="/docs/elements/native/mark/"><code>&lt;mark&gt;</code></a>, <a href="/docs/elements/native/code/"><code>&lt;code&gt;</code></a>, <a href="/docs/elements/native/time/"><code>&lt;time&gt;</code></a>, <a href="/docs/elements/native/data/"><code>&lt;data&gt;</code></a>, etc. But when the content doesn't fit any semantic category, <code>&lt;span&gt;</code> is the right tool.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>When to Use</h2>
    <p>Legitimate uses of <code>&lt;span&gt;</code> in Vanilla Breeze:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Effect targets:</strong> Apply <code>data-effect</code> to a text range within a paragraph</li>
      <li><strong>Status indicators:</strong> The <code>.status</code> class for inline status dots</li>
      <li><strong>Translation control:</strong> <code>translate="no"</code> on brand names or identifiers</li>
      <li><strong>Visually hidden text:</strong> <code>.visually-hidden</code> for screen reader context</li>
      <li><strong>Block progress:</strong> The <code>.block-progress</code> Unicode meter pattern</li>
      <li><strong>Styling hooks:</strong> When CSS needs an inline target that has no semantic equivalent</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>When NOT to Use</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>For emphasis &mdash; use <a href="/docs/elements/native/em/"><code>&lt;em&gt;</code></a> or <a href="/docs/elements/native/strong/"><code>&lt;strong&gt;</code></a></li>
      <li>For highlighted text &mdash; use <a href="/docs/elements/native/mark/"><code>&lt;mark&gt;</code></a></li>
      <li>For code or keyboard input &mdash; use <a href="/docs/elements/native/code/"><code>&lt;code&gt;</code></a> or <a href="/docs/elements/native/kbd/"><code>&lt;kbd&gt;</code></a></li>
      <li>For dates or data values &mdash; use <a href="/docs/elements/native/time/"><code>&lt;time&gt;</code></a> or <a href="/docs/elements/native/data/"><code>&lt;data&gt;</code></a></li>
      <li>For abbreviations &mdash; use <a href="/docs/elements/native/abbr/"><code>&lt;abbr&gt;</code></a></li>
      <li>For headings, navigation, or layout &mdash; always use the semantic element</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Examples</h2>

    <browser-window src="/docs/snippets/demos/span-examples.html" url="span-examples.html" title="Span usage patterns" shadow></browser-window>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Effect Targets</h2>
    <p>When a VB effect needs to wrap a text range inside a paragraph, <code>&lt;span&gt;</code> is the correct container:</p>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Effect target">{{ effectCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Status Indicators</h2>
    <p>The <code>.status</code> class creates an inline status dot using a <code>::before</code> pseudo-element with Unicode characters. Six states are available:</p>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Status indicators">{{ statusCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <code-block language="css" show-lines label="Status CSS">{{ statusCssCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Translation Control</h2>
    <p>Use <code>translate="no"</code> on <code>&lt;span&gt;</code> to prevent machine translation of brand names, identifiers, and technical terms:</p>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Translation control">{{ translateCode | escape }}</code-block>
    <p>See the <a href="/docs/i18n/">i18n guide</a> for VB's full translation convention.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Visually Hidden Text</h2>
    <p>The <code>.visually-hidden</code> class hides text visually while keeping it accessible to screen readers. This provides context that sighted users get from visual cues:</p>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Visually hidden text">{{ visuallyHiddenCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Block Progress</h2>
    <p>A Unicode block-character progress meter using <code>role="meter"</code> for accessibility:</p>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Block progress">{{ blockProgressCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Anti-Patterns</h2>
    <p>Avoid using <code>&lt;span&gt;</code> when a semantic element exists:</p>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Wrong vs right">{{ antiPatternCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><code>&lt;span&gt;</code> has no inherent ARIA role or semantic meaning</li>
      <li>Screen readers treat it as anonymous inline text</li>
      <li>Add <code>role</code>, <code>aria-label</code>, or <code>aria-live</code> when the span carries meaning (e.g., status indicators, meters)</li>
      <li>The <code>.visually-hidden</code> pattern is essential for providing screen reader context that sighted users get visually</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

